# Analysis data

Analysis data represents the **best estimate of the atmospheric state** at a given time.  
It is produced by combining **short-range model forecasts** with **observations** through a process called **data assimilation**.

Neither observations nor model simulations alone can perfectly describe the atmosphere:

- **Observations** contain measurement errors and are **not uniformly distributed** in space. Some regions have dense observation networks, while others have limited coverage.
- **Model simulations** provide complete spatial coverage but rely on approximations of atmospheric processes and may accumulate forecast errors.

Data assimilation combines these two sources of information to produce an **analysis**, which represents the most consistent estimate of the atmospheric state given both observations and model dynamics.

At MeteoSwiss, this analysis is produced using the **KENDA-CH1 ensemble data assimilation system**, which updates the atmospheric state **every hour**.

More information about ensemble data assimilation is available here:  
https://www.meteoswiss.admin.ch/weather/warning-and-forecasting-systems/icon-forecasting-systems/ensemble-data-assimilation.html

