## Available data {#available-data}

### Models' specifications {#models-specifications}

| Attribute | Value |
|-----------|------|
| Assimilation system | KENDA-CH1 |
| Horizontal grid size | approx. 1 km |
| Temporal resolution | 1 hour |
| Ensemble members | Control member only |
| Grid | Native icosahedral |
| Output data format | GRIB edition 2 |

Analysis data represents the atmospheric state **at a specific time**, and is therefore provided **hourly**.

Unlike the forecast datasets, only the **deterministic control member** is distributed in the analysis data.

<br></br>

### Instantaneous analysis fields {#instantaneous-analysis-fields}

Most parameters in the analysis dataset describe the **instantaneous atmospheric state** at the analysis time.

Examples include:

- temperature
- wind
- humidity
- pressure
- cloud variables
- pollen concentrations

These variables represent the **best estimate of the atmosphere at time _t_** and are therefore available at **step = 0**.

<br></br>

### First guess fields {#first-guess-fields}

Some meteorological parameters represent values that are **accumulated, averaged, minimized, or maximized over a period of time**, for example:

- accumulated precipitation
- maximum wind gust
- minimum or maximum temperature

Such quantities cannot represent the instantaneous atmospheric state and therefore **cannot be included in the analysis at time _t_**.

Instead, these parameters are provided from the **first guess of the next assimilation cycle**, available at **step = 1**.

The **first guess** is the short model forecast produced before assimilating the next set of observations.  
Because it represents the atmospheric evolution during the previous hour, it can consistently provide these **time-aggregated variables**.

Since the assimilation cycle runs **every hour**, these first-guess values remain very close in time to the analysis fields.

<br></br>

### Pollen variables {#pollen-variables}

Pollen concentrations are included in the **instantaneous analysis fields** and are updated **every hour**.

These variables are also available in the forecast datasets.

Note that pollen parameters are **added dynamically** depending on the currently active pollen types.  
If a specific pollen variable cannot be found, it may simply mean that the corresponding pollen type is **not currently active** and therefore not present in the dataset.

<br></br>

## Relation to forecasts {#relation-to-forecasts}

The analysis produced by the **KENDA-CH1 assimilation system** provides the **initial conditions for numerical weather forecasts**.

In particular:

- **ICON-CH1-EPS** forecasts are initialized directly from the **KENDA-CH1 analysis** at approximately **1 km resolution**.
- **ICON-CH2-EPS** forecasts also use this analysis as a starting point, but it is **interpolated to the 2 km grid** of the ICON-CH2 model.

The analysis therefore represents the **starting point from which forecasts are launched**.

<br></br>

## Data structure {#data-structure}

The data is provided in **GRIB edition 2** format.

Each GRIB file contains data for:

- one analysis reference time
- one variable
- one model grid
- one temporal step (`step = 0` for analysis, `step = 1` for first guess)

Similar to the forecast datasets, the data is defined on the **native ICON icosahedral grid**.

<br></br>

## FAQ / Troubleshooting

<details>
<summary><b>Why are some accumulated variables not available at step 0?</b></summary>

Accumulated or time-aggregated variables represent values integrated over a time interval (for example precipitation accumulated during the previous hour).

Since the analysis represents the **instantaneous atmospheric state**, such variables cannot be defined at that time.  
They are therefore provided from the **first guess at step = 1**, which represents the model evolution during the previous hour.

</details>

<details>
<summary><b>Why can't I find a specific pollen variable?</b></summary>

Pollen parameters are included dynamically depending on which pollen types are currently active.

If a pollen type is not present in the dataset, it likely means that the pollen season for that species is not currently active.

</details>